<subSubSection lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="428" pageId="15" pageNumber="427" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[816,1429,1790,2019]" box="[816,919,1790,1816]" pageId="15" pageNumber="427">
<emphasis box="[816,919,1790,1816]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="427">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[816,1429,1790,2019]" pageId="15" pageNumber="427">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="E. Geoffroy" baseAuthorityYear="1813" box="[854,1128,1824,1850]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="427" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="diadema">
<emphasis box="[854,1128,1824,1850]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="427">Hipposideros diadema</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was the largest hipposiderid species in the study area (
<tableCitation box="[1210,1302,1857,1883]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="10.[99,112,501,522]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="TABLE 2. Measurements of nine external traits of 52 bat species. FA — forearm length, BM — body mass, HB — head and body length, TL — tail length, TB — tibia length, HF — hind foot length, TU — thumb length: EL — ear length, TR — tragus length. Numbers denote minimum and maximum, and sample size; values in parentheses indicate measurements of specimens of this study; ‘ – ’: data not available. BMs for specimens were taken in the field. All measurements in mm, except for BM (in g)" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/1DCD6623FFA8BF319968FE17FA147437" pageId="15" pageNumber="427" tableUuid="1DCD6623FFA8BF319968FE17FA147437">Table 2</tableCitation>
). It can be easily distinguished from other 
<taxonomicName box="[1196,1353,1891,1917]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="427" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1196,1353,1891,1917]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="427">Hipposideros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its larger body size and a distinct white, cream, or yellow flash along the side of each shoulder, which extends as a stripe down the side of the upperparts.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[159,771,223,384]" pageId="16" pageNumber="428">
It is primarily a cave-roosting bat (
<bibRefCitation author="Kingston" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Kingston" pageId="16" pageNumber="428" refId="ref26934" refString="KINGSTON, T., B. L. LIM, and A. ZUBAID. 2006. Bats of Krau Wildlife Reserve. Penerbit Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia, Bangi, 145 pp." type="book" year="2006">
Kingston 
<emphasis box="[702,764,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="428">et al.</emphasis>
, 2006
</bibRefCitation>
), and has been recorded roosting with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Horsfield" authorityYear="1823" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="428" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="428">Rhinolophus affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
at a cave in Penggerukan, 
<collectingRegion country="Indonesia" name="Sumatera Utara" pageId="16" pageNumber="428">North Sumatra</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Whitten" box="[241,482,324,350]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Whitten" pageId="16" pageNumber="428" refId="ref28927" refString="WHITTEN, A. J., S. J. DAMNIK, J. ANWAR, and N. HISYAM. 2000. Chapter Ten: caves. Pp. 313 - 336, in The ecology of Sumatra, 1 st periplus edition. Tuttle Publishing, North Clarendo, xxxix + 478 pp." type="book" year="2000">
Whitten 
<emphasis box="[345,403,324,350]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="428">et al.</emphasis>
, 2000
</bibRefCitation>
). Our finding extends its distribution from northern 
<collectingRegion box="[475,573,358,384]" country="Indonesia" name="Sumatera Utara" pageId="16" pageNumber="428">Sumatra</collectingRegion>
to the south.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
